               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390617-name-1429" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390617-name-1429" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390617-name-1429" type="surname" value="STEWART"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390617-name-1429" type="given" value="DONALD"></interp>DONALD STEWART</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable E</hi> 35.) I was on duty on the 31st of May at Deptford. At a quarter past ten o'clock at night, I met the prisoner carrying a plank about one hundred yards from the prosecutor's—I asked How he came by it—he said he had taken it from a beer-shop, and was taking it to Old King-street, that it belonged to Mr. Sanders, and had been kept in a house in Butcher-row—I took him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390617-name-1430" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390617-name-1430" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390617-name-1430" type="surname" value="WALEDGE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390617-name-1430" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS WALEDGE</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a shipwright. This plank is mine—I pur<lb></lb>chased it and worked it in a barge that belonged to Mr. Fyffe, at the Pier wharf, Deptford—I left it safe at half-past eight o'clock in the evening of the 31st—I knew the prisoner, but he did not work there.</p>
               <p>
